Package Graphs

Class GraphTraversal

  • java.lang.Object
    • Graphs.GraphTraversal

  • public class GraphTraversal
extends java.lang.Object
    This class implements some of the basic traversal and search methods: depth-first, breadth-first and iterative deepening. The implementation is generic and therefore usable for all kinds of search trees and search DAGs.

      • breadthFirst

        public static <N,V> V breadthFirst​(N node,
                                   boolean inclusive,
                                   java.util.function.Function<N,java.lang.Object> successors,
                                   java.util.function.Function<N,V> function)
        This is the classical breadth-first search algorithm without any optimizations. It stops the first time the 'successors' returns a non-null value. If the structure is actually a DAG then nodes which are reachable via different paths may actually be visited multiple times.
        A breadth-first search without any optimization needs an array where the levels are stored. Therefore breadth-first search may require lots of memory.
        Type Parameters:
        N - the node type.
        V - the result type of the function.
        Parameters:
        node - the start node of the search tree
        inclusive - if true then the start node is checked as well.
        successors - maps a node to a stream or collection of successor nodes.
        function - a successors to be applied to the nodes.
        Returns:
        the first non-null successors value.

      • breadthFirst

        public static <N extends Timestamped,V> V breadthFirst​(N node,
                                                       boolean inclusive,
                                                       int timestamp,
                                                       java.util.function.Function<N,java.lang.Object> successors,
                                                       java.util.function.Function<N,V> function)
        This is the classical breadth-first search algorithm, but with an optimization for DAGs. It stops the first time the 'successors' returns a non-null value. The methods works for classes which implement the Timestamped interface. Timestamps are used to avoid visiting the same node multiple times.
        A breadth-first search without any optimization needs a items array where the levels are stored. Therefore breadth first-search may double the DAG's memory.
        Type Parameters:
        N - the node type.
        V - the result type of the successors.
        Parameters:
        node - the start node of the search tree
        inclusive - if true then the start node is checked as well.
        timestamp - a timestamp value, larger than the timestamps of all nodes in the search tree.
        successors - maps a node to a stream or collection of successor nodes.
        function - a successors to be applied to the nodes.
        Returns:
        the first non-null successors value.

      • depthFirst

        public static <N,V> V depthFirst​(N node,
                                 boolean inclusive,
                                 java.util.function.Function<N,java.lang.Object> successors,
                                 java.util.function.Function<N,V> function)
        This is the classical depth-first search algorithm without any optimizations. It stops the first time the 'successors' returns a non-null value. If the structure is actually a DAG then nodes which are reachable via different paths may actually be visited multiple times.
        The algorithm is recursive and therefore uses only the stack as items memory.

        function - a successors to be applied to the nodes.
        Returns:
        the first non-null successors value.

      • iterativeDeepening

        public static <N,V> V iterativeDeepening​(N node,
                                         boolean inclusive,
                                         java.util.function.Function<N,java.lang.Object> successors,
                                         java.util.function.Function<N,V> function)
        This is the classical iterative deepening search algorithm. It stops the first time the 'successors' returns a non-null value. Iterative deepening is a depth-limited depth-first search, where depth-limit is gradually increased. It therefore looks like a breadth-first search, but needs no extra memory. If the branching rate of the nodes is larger than 2 then the iteration at most doubles the time compared to the unbounded depth-first search.
        Type Parameters:
        N - the node type.
        V - the result type of the successors.
        Parameters:
        node - the start node of the search tree
        inclusive - if true then the start node is checked as well.
        successors - maps a node to a stream or collection of successor nodes.
        function - a successors to be applied to the nodes.
        Returns:
        the first non-null successors value.
